<!-- INTRODUCTION -->
<p>Walk into any clinic break room right now, and you'll hear the same conversation: "My patient asked about Ozempic again today."</p>

<p>As an internal medicine physician, I've watched this medication transform from a diabetes treatment into a cultural phenomenon. Celebrities mention it. Social media floods with before-and-after photos. And every day, patients come to my office asking the same question:</p>

<p><strong>"Can you prescribe Ozempic for weight loss?"</strong></p>

<p>It's a fair question. The results are impressive‚Äîsometimes dramatic. But as with any powerful medication, the real story is more nuanced than Instagram suggests.</p>

<p>In this guide, I'll give you the same information I share with my patients: what Ozempic actually does, who it helps most, the side effects I warn everyone about, and the hard truths that weight loss clinics don't always mention.</p>

<!-- WHAT IS OZEMPIC -->
<h2>What Exactly Is Ozempic? (A Doctor's Explanation)</h2>

<p>Ozempic is the brand name for <strong>semaglutide</strong>, a medication that belongs to a class called <strong>GLP-1 receptor agonists</strong>.</p>

<p>Here's what that means in plain language: Your body naturally produces a hormone called GLP-1 when you eat. This hormone tells your pancreas to release insulin, signals your liver to stop producing sugar, and communicates with your brain that you're full.</p>

<p>Semaglutide is a synthetic version that <strong>amplifies that signal dramatically</strong>.</p>

<p>Originally approved by the FDA in 2017 for type 2 diabetes, Ozempic gained attention when researchers noticed something unexpected: patients weren't just controlling their blood sugar‚Äîthey were losing significant weight.</p>

<h3>How It Works for Weight Loss</h3>

<table>
    <tr>
        <th>Mechanism</th>
        <th>What Happens</th>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td><strong>Appetite suppression</strong></td>
        <td>Directly affects brain appetite centers, reducing "food noise"</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td><strong>Delayed gastric emptying</strong></td>
        <td>Food stays in stomach longer, increasing fullness after meals</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td><strong>Insulin regulation</strong></td>
        <td>Stable blood sugar reduces cravings and overeating</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td><strong>Possible fat metabolism effects</strong></td>
        <td>Emerging research suggests direct effects on fat tissue</td>
    </tr>
</table>

<div class="doctor-note">
    <strong>üë®‚Äç‚öïÔ∏è My clinical take:</strong> When patients ask how Ozempic "really" works, I tell them this: "It turns down the volume on food noise." Many people don't realize how much mental energy they spend thinking about food until that noise quiets.
</div>

<!-- OZEMPIC VS WEGOVY -->
<h2>Ozempic vs. Wegovy: What's the Difference?</h2>

<p>Patients often ask: "If Ozempic works for weight loss, why is there another drug called Wegovy?"</p>

<p>Great question. Here's the answer:</p>

<table>
    <tr>
        <th></th>
        <th>Ozempic</th>
        <th>Wegovy</th>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td><strong>Active ingredient</strong></td>
        <td>Semaglutide</td>
        <td>Semaglutide</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td><strong>FDA approved for</strong></td>
        <td>Type 2 diabetes</td>
        <td>Weight management</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td><strong>Dose strengths</strong></td>
        <td>0.5 mg, 1 mg, 2 mg</td>
        <td>0.25 mg up to 2.4 mg</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td><strong>Insurance coverage</strong></td>
        <td>Better for diabetes</td>
        <td>Variable for weight loss</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td><strong>Same manufacturer</strong></td>
        <td colspan="2" style="text-align: center;">Novo Nordisk</td>
    </tr>
</table>

<p><strong>They are the same drug</strong>, but Wegovy is specifically approved for weight loss and titrated to higher doses.</p>

<p>In practice, many physicians (myself included) prescribe Ozempic "off-label" for weight loss when appropriate. This is legal and common, though insurance may not cover it without a diabetes diagnosis.</p>

<div class="doctor-note">
    <strong>üë®‚Äç‚öïÔ∏è My clinical approach:</strong> If a patient has diabetes + needs weight loss, Ozempic is first-line. If they need weight loss only, I discuss both options, including cost and coverage realities.
</div>

