<p class="highlight-green"><strong>Key takeaway:</strong> Newer medications (Mounjaro/Zepbound) may produce greater weight loss, but Ozempic/Wegovy have the longest safety track record.</p>

<!-- CLINICAL DATA -->
<h2>Does Ozempic Actually Work? The Evidence</h2>

<p>The short answer: <strong>Yes, significantly better than anything we've had before.</strong></p>

<p>The long answer requires looking at the <strong>STEP trials</strong> (Semaglutide Treatment Effect in People with obesity), published in the <em>New England Journal of Medicine</em> (2021).</p>

<h3>Key Findings from STEP 1:</h3>
<ul>
    <li><strong>Average weight loss after 68 weeks:</strong> 14.9% of body weight</li>
    <li><strong>Placebo group:</strong> 2.4% (diet/exercise alone)</li>
    <li><strong>Participants losing ‚â•15%:</strong> 50% on semaglutide vs. 5% on placebo</li>
    <li><strong>Participants losing ‚â•20%:</strong> 32% on semaglutide vs. 2% on placebo</li>
</ul>

<p>To put that in perspective: A 200-pound person lost about <strong>30 pounds on average</strong>. Half lost 30 pounds or more. A third lost 40 pounds or more.</p>

<div class="doctor-note">
    <strong>üë®‚Äç‚öïÔ∏è Real-world results in my clinic:</strong>
    <ul style="margin-top: 10px; margin-bottom: 0;">
        <li>Patients who lose 25-30 pounds and maintain it</li>
        <li>Patients who lose minimally (usually due to side effects or inconsistent dosing)</li>
        <li>Patients who lose significant weight but regain when stopping</li>
    </ul>
</div>

<!-- WHO IS A CANDIDATE -->
<h2>Who Is Actually a Candidate? (Clinical Criteria)</h2>

<p>Clinical guidelines (AACE, Endocrine Society) recommend considering GLP-1 agonists like Ozempic for:</p>

<div class="success-box">
    <strong>‚úÖ Good candidates:</strong>
    <ul>
        <li>BMI ‚â•30 (obesity)</li>
        <li>BMI ‚â•27 with at least one weight-related condition:
            <ul>
                <li>Hypertension</li>
                <li>Type 2 diabetes</li>
                <li>Dyslipidemia (high cholesterol)</li>
                <li>Obstructive sleep apnea</li>
                <li>Cardiovascular disease</li>
                <li>Nonalcoholic fatty liver disease</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
        <li>Failed previous weight loss attempts (diet, exercise, other programs)</li>
        <li>Motivated to make lifestyle changes</li>
    </ul>
</div>

<div class="danger-box">
    <strong>‚ùå Not good candidates:</strong>
    <ul>
        <li>BMI <27 without complications</li>
        <li>Personal or family history of medullary thyroid cancer</li>
        <li>MEN2 syndrome (multiple endocrine neoplasia)</li>
        <li>History of pancreatitis</li>
        <li>Severe gastroparesis</li>
        <li>Pregnancy, planning pregnancy, or breastfeeding</li>
        <li>Active eating disorder (anorexia, bulimia)</li>
    </ul>
</div>

<h3>My Screening Questions</h3>
<ol>
    <li>"What have you tried before?" (establishes failed attempts)</li>
    <li>"How would you describe your eating patterns?" (screens for disordered eating)</li>
    <li>"Any family history of thyroid cancer?" (non-negotiable red flag)</li>
    <li>"Are you planning pregnancy in the next year?" (medication must be stopped 2 months before)</li>
</ol>

<!-- WEEKLY SCHEDULE FOR PATIENTS -->
<h2>Your First Month on Ozempic: A Week-by-Week Schedule</h2>

<p>Starting Ozempic can feel overwhelming. Here's exactly what I tell my patients to expect:</p>

<table class="schedule-table">
    <tr>
        <th>Week</th>
        <th>Dose</th>
        <th>What to Expect</th>
        <th>Tips</th>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td>Week 1</td>
        <td>0.25 mg</td>
        <td>Mild appetite reduction; possible mild nausea</td>
        <td>Inject before bed; eat light dinner; hydrate</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td>Week 2</td>
        <td>0.25 mg</td>
        <td>Body adjusting; nausea may peak then improve</td>
        <td>Small, frequent meals; avoid fatty foods</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td>Week 3</td>
        <td>0.25 mg</td>
        <td>Appetite suppression more noticeable</td>
        <td>Focus on protein intake (25g/meal)</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td>Week 4</td>
        <td>0.25 mg</td>
        <td>Stable; preparing for dose increase</td>
        <td>Track any side effects to report</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td>Week 5-6</td>
        <td>0.5 mg</td>
        <td>Increased effect; nausea may return briefly</td>
        <td>Same precautions as Week 1-2</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td>Week 7-8+</td>
        <td>1 mg (if needed)</td>
        <td>Full therapeutic effect</td>
        <td>Continue healthy habits</td>
    </tr>
</table>

<div class="doctor-note">
    <strong>üë®‚Äç‚öïÔ∏è Pro tip:</strong> I tell patients to pick a consistent injection day (I recommend Sunday night). If side effects occur, they hit over the weekend when you can rest, not during work.
</div>

<h3>Sample Weekly Schedule (Starting Week 1)</h3>

<table>
